r /><br />But I'd hate to make all those loops etc (that the compiler can<br />currently almost always trivially turn into trivial unconditional<br />non-loops) be sometrhing that ends up testing a bit and having a<br />conditional.<br /><br />I wonder if we could have some checking mode or something that at<br />least makes those things easier to notice.  But I don't see a sane way<br />to do that statically.<br /><br />Looking at that patch of yours, it seems to depend on<br />'watchdog_allowed_mask' having just been initialized as empty, which<br />is the case that doesn't work well for UP. So there isn't even any<br />code to trigger on, it would have to be some added warning to all<br />users that does something along the lines of 'WARN_ON_ONCE(cpumask !=<br />1)'<br /><br />.. and then hardly anybody would run that configuration anyway.<br /><br />Annoying.<br /><br />              Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
